              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Recognizing player types</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=259"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=259"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=443">Douglas "Douglas" Harvilla</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 443 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">  A description of the three types of players (by level of aggression) and where the new player should try to fit in.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">  At Star Wars tournaments, you will encounter all kinds of people.  That's part of the fun.  Everyone plays at a different level, with a style all her/his own.  But dividing them up into three groups serves our purposes just fine.<br>
<br>
  Everyone you run into at a SW:CCG tournament has either a Timid, Aggressive, or Dangerous play style.  These change over time, and generally the players become cautiously aggressive.  Let's take a look at each play type of play style.<br>
<br>
  Timid players don't like taking chances.  They are often intimidated by more experienced players, who they really don't feel they can beat. They will often deploy their characters somewhere away from the opponent's forces and just try to win the drain race.	Or they may not deploy very many cards at all, worried about being pounded in a battle.<br>
<br>
  Usually, this play style develops after a particularly nasty deck type in the hands of an experienced player delivers a few killing blows.  The memory of these encounters makes the timid player freeze up and become indecisive.  These players feel uncomfortable when they are ahead, like the hammer could fall at any moment.  And they feel like they've already lost when things turn against them.<br>
<br>
  Timid players will almost always lose to Aggressive players, but will occasionally win against Dangerous players.  Timid players tend to win half or less of their games.  This is the group of players most likely to become discouraged and give up tournaments, so take care not to upset them by bragging or being rude.	Try to help them gain some more confidence and they will soon be putting up a hard fight.<br>
<br>
  Aggressive players aren't really fond of taking chances either, but will do so when the need arises.  Unlike the Timid players, they will put up a savage fight when cornered, and most timed-out games are the result of a pairing between two closely matched Aggressive players.<br>
<br>
  When Vader is draining away with his lightsaber at the Cantina, for instance, an Aggressive player might drop down Luke With Lightsaber if necessary, and if he/she has some reason to expect high battle destiny draws.  A Timid player would probably deploy Luke to a different nearby site, fearing a duel or a terrible outcome from the battle.<br>
<br>
  Aggressive players will almost always win against Timid players, but will lose some games to Dangerous players.  Enough that they should become familiar with such players in their area and take extra care when confronting them.  Aggressive players are, in general, very consistent and tend to win 3/4 of their games or go undefeated.<br>
<br>
  Players who take risks willingly, early and often, fit in the Dangerous category.  Why are they 'dangerous'?  Because if one of their long-shot desperation moves pays off, it could land the opponent in serious trouble.<br>
<br>
  These players have been known to drop EPP Luke against Darth Vader on the second turn, with no way of knowing how the destiny draws will come up, and battle.  Or to start Epic Duels very early in the game, taking the chance that the opponent has no dueling defenses in hand and relying on sheer chance for the win.<br>
<br>
  This will lead to a fair number of losses, since the cards don't always come up the way we'd like.	So the Dangerous player will occasionally lose a game to a Timid player, after making a bold move and watching it go disastrously wrong.  But it also means he/she will win some games against Aggressive players, perhaps against the 'Top Guns' in the area.<br>
<br>
  Dangerous players tend to be rather inconsistent, but almost always fare better in tournaments than Timid players.  And they win now and then, as well.  Sometimes with very powerful themes everyone has stopped loading counters for.<br>
<br>
  If you are a consistent player, you will often use a game against a Timid player as a 'springboard,' giving you a cushion of differential.	Or to help you recover after losing a game.  Some Timid players won't put up any resistance after a battle or two, and in this case you should deploy as few cards as possible if you are in desperate need of differential to get back into competition.<br>
<br>
  When you run into Dangerous players, take a little bit more caution than normal.  Realize that even an early encounter with Vader can mean an Epic Duel, or that leaving Vader alone can invite an attack from an EPP main character, and be prepared.<br>
<br>
  You can often take advantage of a Dangerous player's eagerness to make a breakthrough.  For instance, moving Vader's escorts away and leaving him open to attack while you are holding I Have You Now for use against Luke.<br>
<br>
  If you are new to this game and aren't sure which category you fit into, here is a word of advice.  It is far better to be a Dangerous player than a Timid player.  Without making a few blunders and pulling off a few minor miracles, you will not gain experience in this game.<br>
<br>
  And if your collection of cards isn't very large yet, you won't have access to the main characters and 'big' rares.  So keep your destiny average high, it will be the one big advantage your deck has over the expensive decks.	You will flip higher destiny draws on average if you are using Eloms and all kinds of aliens.<br>
<br>
  Use a powerful theme your opponents are not accustomed to seeing.  Most players are aware of the existence of 'insert' cards like 3,720 to 1 and Never Tell Me The Odds, but few actually use enough counter cards to protect themselves from these nasty effects.	Even a Hunt Down deck has something to fear from Eloms and insert cards.<br>
<br>
  Eventually, as you gain experience and get more powerful cards, you will become good at techniques such as destiny tracking.	And you will learn to spot the appropriate times to press the attack and take risks.<br>
  Then you will become a very consistent player.<br>
<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=259"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=259"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=259" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
